div.p:
Jealouie had oon inpir'd her with an immortal hatred againt me, and I was like to feel its cruel Effects: You have deprived me of all my comfort, dangerous Ariania, aid he one day to me, and you have rewarded the incere confidence of my Heart with Perfidiounes;


but believe what I ay, this place in pires no moderation; and whatever kindnes I am forced to hew you, may be oon changed into hatred. Fear mine, ince you have o baely erved me. I am o far from deerving thee Reproaches, reply'd I, with a edate mind, that I feel neither remores of Concience, nor terrour at the hearing of them. My Behaviour had been always innocent; I never endeavoured to pleae the Sultan; and as for your confidence, Heaven knows whether I have abued it: But you loved Scanderberg, reply'd he, and when I acquainted you with my paion; you hid your Sentiments from me with a criminal Diimulation: Suppoe what you ay was true, anwer'd I, you have yet no reaon to accue me, did not your Jealouie blind you. Was I obliged to open my heart to you, by reaon of your confidence, which I o little deired? And intead of complaining of me, ought you not to commend my prudence for not declaring my elf your Rival? But Selimana, let us not trouble our elves any longer about what is pat, or what is to come: Let us conider, that Scanderberg is like to be King of Albania, that we are Slaves,


and that I would willingly give mot of my Blood to regain you the Sultan's love; if you are acquainted with my endeavour, you may know how I deal with him. Alas! reply'd he, your only deire is to ee Scanderberg again, and that Crown you talk of, renders him more lovely to your Eyes: But tho' Fortune confines me here, you are alo like to hare the ame Fate.
